Outlier VIF

!! Variables that are correlated with each other dont have a higher chance of interacting with each other in a model. Interaction means that the effect of one on the outcome will depend on the other. While correlation only means that the 2 variables tend to vary together in a linear fashion. And the latter says nothing about the effect of each on the outcome Y

Backward model: crm_1000 ~ pop18 + docs + beds + poverty + pcincome + region + pop_density

Read in

crime_df = 
  read_csv("cdi.csv") %>% 
  mutate(
    region = factor(region),
    pop_density = pop / area,
    crm_1000 = 1000 * crimes / pop
  ) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-crimes, -id, -area, -pop) %>% 
  dplyr::select(crm_1000, everything()) %>%
  drop_na()

    poverty + pcincome + totalinc + pop_density, data = backward_df)

doc_totalinc = lm(crm_1000 ~ poverty + hsgrad + beds + docs + region + pop_density + beds * docs + beds * totalinc, data = model_1_df)

bed_totalinc = lm(crm_1000 ~ poverty + hsgrad + beds + docs + region + pop_density + beds * docs + docs * totalinc, data = model_2_df)
